postcontent:
.62 Caliber, 30" octagonal barrel with a fair-good bore that has some light pitting within the grooves. Commercially manufactured rifle built for military matches and so has an integral bayonet rail on the right side near the muzzle with the barrel retaining 95-97% of the maker re-applied browned finish with silvering along the edges of the facets and some pinprick pitting at the breech. Breech, hammer, and lockplate have minimal engraving with "COGSWELL 221 STRAND LONDON" along the top barrel flat and "COGSWELL" on the lockplate. The rifle has its original brass-tipped wooden ramrod and is held by a plain thimble with ridged tail-pipe.

Period non-original fixed sights are installed and the lock has a darkly mottled gray-brown patina mixing with old added blue. The triggerguard has the same minimal engraving with pineapple finial and a dark gray overall patina with spots of mild surface freckling. The full length walnut stock is fastened by two wedges with plain oval brass escutcheons and has lovely figuring throughout with some scattered very minor handling marks and small surface blemishes marring the excellent varnish finish. The rifle has its original brass-tipped wooden ramrod and is held by a plain thimble with ridged tail-pipe. This is a very attractive percussion rifle in fine-near excellent condition with an unusual integral bayonet attachment. I will only ship to individual with Valid Driver's License as this is an antique.

title: For Sale:  WARNING TO ALL MUST READ !!!!!
postcontent: Had to share my experience as its a perfect example of why you should look over a used firearm even at a FFL. Found a Hi Power with a broken safety that would allow the  hammer to strike the firing pin and would discharge told the owner who at first said its normal (yeah right last time I checked a Hi Power should not be able to discharge with the safety on) but then took it out back for "work". A few days later its still in  the case same price no note of caution assuming it was fixed I took a look an same safety problem and still not sitting flush with the frame creating a condition where it could fire while partially locking the slide (awsome way to loose a eye when the safety sheers off) asked employes why its not fixed and they never knew the owner simply put it back the employee looked and confirmed it was broken still and said "its an accident waiting to happen". Would not trust a repair by them anyway having heard from an employee to using YouTube as their repair guide a couple years ago when discussing a modified Glock. So I looked at a Glock instead only to find a crack on the slide confirmed by an employee it was quickly dismissed by the owner again by saying "its a Glock its fine" and back in the case it went to wait for its new unfortunate owner at no price change or warning. This makes me think the owner would rather make a quick couple hundred than worry about the safety of the customer. Unfortunately this is just a week I could go on forever about this place. If any concerned buyers on the south shore/coast have any concerns feel free to ask. Some dealers are great and check out every used gun but others like this one put profit before people so know what you looking at and look close its really the new or inexperienced buyers that will loose the most by places like this and make the mistake of trusting the dealers word.

Again, as per customer request, Buffalo Bore has developed two new 35 Whelen loads. Item 42A features a Sierra 225gr. SPTZ-BT bullet @ 2705 fps out of my Remington 700. (24 inch bbl)  At the expected impact velocities, this bullet will mushroom readily, but hold together on large game like bull elk. We recommend this load for use on smallish big game (like whitetail deer) through Yukon Moose and Bison. However, on very tough (other than broadside) angling shots on large big game, we recommend the use of our item 42B, which features a 225gr. Barnes TSX bullet @ 2654 fps out of the same rifle. If you desire the deepest possible penetration from an expanding bullet in 35 Whelen, the 225gr. Barnes TSX bullet delivers. It will out penetrate a 250gr. typical premium partition bullet, but gives the advantage of higher velocity, flatter trajectory and reduced recoil of the lighter 225gr. bullet. You can use this TSX load for bad angle (quartering or going straight away) shots on the largest North American big game.

This ammo is designed to be the highest quality, most powerful/versatile, 35 Whelen ammo, in the world. It exhibits sub MOA accuracy in our test rifle.

title: For Sale:  Big shiny package would look good under the tree - 50AE Desert Eagle
postcontent:
Here is a beautiful handfull.  A Desert Eagle Mark XIX in .50 ae.  A totally-impractical-complete-overkill-but-still-gotta-have-one-chunk-of-steel.  I believe I am the third owner, but this beauty does not appear to have been shot much at all.  I know I haven't shot it much (< 20 rds).  I would rate condition as excellent.  This is the original Mark XIX made in Israel by Israel Military Industries (IMI).  It was one of the first batch before they brought production to the US in 1995.  I have read that later models had reliability issues, so this is one of the good ones.  According to Magnum Research, this particular gun was manufactured in 1994, so it was one of the later ones in this first batch.

The finish appears to be matte chrome, but it could be brushed chrome or satin nickel - I cannot tell from pictures on the internet.  Come take a look and make an offer.  I am only selling because I have bought too many guns.  Comes with original box, docs, and disassembly tool.

If interested, call or text Perry at 770-826-933Eight.
